This warning against the undue influence of the army is justified by the later history of Rome, when it had become a purely prosessional body. In the last century of the Republic, when the Senate was corrupt, and the ‘comitia' only represented a fraction of the citizens, the situation was decided in turn by the armies of Marius, Sulla, Pompey, and Caesar; and the principate established by Augustus tested on his command of the armies of the state.
